passages.text: UK | Computer Services & IT Consulting Softcat

A Year of AdjustmentsA FY25 trading statement is slightly ahead, but driven by hard-to-predict large deals. We think this creates complexity, and the potential non-recurrence of such deals puts downward pressure on FY26/7 consensus. Meanwhile, for much of the next 12 months, we will be discussing adjusted growth and adjusted profits. We continue to see better value elsewhere, though we nudge our PT to 1,400p.

Key headlines: Softcat has announced a strong finish to FY25 and now sees EBIT growth in the mid- teens, up from low teens. This implies FY25 EBIT of c.177m vs company- compiled consensus at £174m. However, this outperformance (just as it was at the 3Q stage) is led by large deals that are harder to forecast.

Looking ahead, excluding large deals from FY25, management expects to deliver the usual framework of low double- digit gross profits growth and high single- digit EBIT growth. Assuming the high single- digit is \(9\%\) , this implies FY26 EBIT of £185m (marginally below consensus at £188m) and FY27 EBIT of c.200m (vs cons at £207.5m).

Size matters: Softcat notes that excluding large deals, the FY25 base is £170m. This implies large deals contribute c.7m of EBIT. In the context of the size of Softcat, it would be hard to argue that a £1- 2m deal is unusually large. As a result, we assume the majority of this £7m comes from one client, leading the company to view it as unusually large. Based on our recollection, Softcat last called out a large customer contribution in FY22, when one customer accounted for \(10\%\) of GII. This highlights the unpredictable nature of larger deals and the challenge in knowing how to extrapolate this going forward.

Sustainable growth: Treating £170m of EBIT as the core base implies underlying growth in FY25 was \(c.10\%\) . We think this matches investor perceptions of Softcat as a double- digit grower. But it also means that investors will likely assume that high- single- digit growth guidance is conservative. As a result, we expect consensus to remain above company guidance.

Adjusted metrics: On a reported basis, FY26 EBIT growth will be just \(c.5\%\) and for the next 12 months, we will need to discuss "adjusted growth" off this theoretical base, excluding large deals. Meanwhile, the P&L will include exceptions, so "adjusted EBIT" will be the new definition. On a reported IFRS basis, there may well be limited EBIT growth, if at all.

Forecasts and valuation: Given investor sentiment assumes Softcat is a double- digit grower, we reflect this in our forecasts, assuming EBIT growth continues at \(10\%\) . This leads to immaterial \(c.1\%\) revisions to FY26/7 EBIT, leaving forecasts ahead of company guidance, e.g., FY26 EBIT at £187m vs the implied guide at £185m. We continue to value Softcat on a DCF basis, and slightly stronger FCF in FY25 leads to a revised PT of 1400p. We continue to see better value elsewhere in the sector and maintain our Underperform stance.
Please see analyst certifications, important disclosure information, and information regarding the status of non-US analysts on pages 4-9 of this report. \\* Jefferies International Limited

Softcat is a well- run business with one of the best track records. However, the recent share price outperformance has run ahead of fundamentals, making Softcat one of the most expensive names in the European technology sector.
Against the backdrop of continuing soft UK macro data, a lack of upgrade momentum is likely to lead to continued multiple pressure.
Risk/Reward - 12 Month View

- Softcat continues to increase its share of customer wallet, enabling it to increase UK IT spending by a factor of \(>2x\) over the next three years.- Best-in-class productivity and lean cost structure allow Softcat to defend the current level of profitability – driving an uplift in EBIT over the period.- 9.5% cost of capital, terminal growth 3%- DCF-based PT = 1,400p.

- Initiatives to increase customer wallet share result in Softcat accelerating the pace of wallet share gains – driving double-digit gross invoiced income growth.- Leads to improved long-term growth of 3.5% and a reduction in the cost of capital to 8%- DCF-based PT = 1,945p.

- UK IT investments go into a cyclical downturn, although offset partly by increased wallet share growth and gross invoiced income growth slows.- Terminal growth falls to 2% and the cost of capital increases to 10%- DCF-based PT = 1,245p.

Top- ranked ESG issue: Energy management - Softcat identifies the implementation of the decarbonization agenda into its day- to- day operations and services to help customers achieve their sustainability goals as the primary areas of focus.
Company target(s): 1) Became carbon- neutral for scopes 1 and 2 in 2022 and has maintained ever since, 2) Already uses 100% renewable energy in all offices, 3) Aiming to be net zero by 2040.

1. How is Softcat going to compete against other competitors to ensure environmentally friendly supplies from technology vendors as the topic of sustainability becomes increasingly common among customers? 
2. What infrastructures are in place to ensure accountability when incorporating ESG factors into business decision-making and daily operations?

Softcat, a provider of IT infrastructure, is one of the UK's top 5 value- added resellers (VARs). Softcat was established in 1993 by Peter Kelly, the company's largest shareholder, as a software catalogue (the origin of the company's name). The company has evolved considerably over the last decade from a strong position as a mid- market Microsoft reseller to being able to deliver a much broader IT solutions capability. Softcat now serves some 12,000+ UK customers across a vendor base that includes nearly all of the technology vendors.

Our DCF- based PT is based on a \(9.5\%\) WACC and \(3\%\) long- term growth rate. Key risks: lower- than- expected returns on Softcat's growth initiatives, failure to develop a successful services offering, and worse than expected macro.
